Monday marks 62-years since the Sharpeville massacre where 69 unarmed people were killed by apartheid police. For more on Human Rights Day, Tumelo Mothotoane spoke with the President of the Black Consciousness Movement - United, Hlulani Mabasa. Courtesy of #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - The Black Conscious Movement-United has joined the call for Human Rights Day to be renamed Sharpeville Day. Monday marks 62 years since the Sharpeville Massacre where 69 unarmed people were killed at the hands of the apartheid police. WATCH: Discussion | Remembering the 1960 Sharpeville massacre They were protesting against unjust pass laws. Hlulani Mabasa, President of the Black Consciousness Movement - United, said: "It's not only [the] Sharpeville Massacre which has been changed it also June 16, Soweto Uprising you see concerted effort to ensure that these days are not called what they are because they are afraid that they bring bad memories to those who benefited from colonialism at the same time they are distorting history".